<h1 id="sign-inform-loaded-over-http">Sign-inÂ form loaded over HTTP</h1>

<p>Yes you read that right. Even though the form is POSTing to HTTPS by then it is <a href="https://www.troyhunt.com/your-login-form-posts-to-https-but-you/">too late</a>. An attacker could have already intercepted the initial HTTP response and pointed the form to the URL of his choosing.</p>

<p>Sometimes websites still offer sign-in over HTTPS when you look for it but it doesnâ€™t seem to be the case here.Â  <a href="https://secure.beinsportsconnect.com.au/">https://secure.beinsportsconnect.com.au/</a> redirects toÂ <a href="http://www.beinsportsconnect.com.au/">http://www.beinsportsconnect.com.au/</a>Â and trying to access <a href="https://www.beinsportsconnect.com.au/">https://www.beinsportsconnect.com.au/</a>Â results in something you should never see:</p>

